{"accepted":[{"assertion":"Formal-Conjectures statement: Erdos1063.erdos_1063.variants.cambie_upper_bound https://google-deepmind.github.io/formal-conjectures/theorem/?name=Erdos1063.erdos_1063.variants.cambie_upper_bound.","id":"vf_dda44e804e8b97de","trust":"signed","type":"theoretical"},{"assertion":"Erdős Problem #1063: declared status 'open'. Formalized: yes. Let $k\\geq 2$ and define $n_k\\geq 2k$ to be the least value of $n$ such that $n-i$ divides $\\binom{n}{k}$ for all but one $0\\leq i<k$. Estimate $n_k$. Current best: Erd\\H{o}s and Selfridge noted (and a proof can be found in \\cite{Mo85}) that if $n\\geq 2k$ then there must exist at least one $0\\leq i<k$ such that $n-i$ does not divide $\\binom{n}{k}$. Monier \\cite{Mo85} observed that $n_k\\leq k!$ for $k\\geq 3$, since $\\binom{k!}{k}$ is divisible by $k!-i$ for $1\\leq i<k$. Cambie observes in the comments that this can be improved to\\[n_k\\leq k[2,3,\\ldots,k-1]\\leq e^{(1+o(1))k},\\]where $[\\cdots]$ is the least common multiple. Prize: no. OEIS: A389360. Tags: number theory.","id":"vf_e73b8515e9b26298","trust":"signed","type":"theoretical"}],"accepted_activity":false,"activity":[],"activity_types":[],"attempt_count":0,"banked_attempt_count":0,"commits":[],"dependency_impact":"none","detail_url":"problems/1063.json","draft_proposals":[],"edges":[{"evidence":"Problem identity derived from the accepted finding's pinned source anchor.","inferred":true,"relation":"describes","source":"vf_dda44e804e8b97de","source_root":"sha256:540d4967071425f77c693e61f62053208b07d67667490dcb9eeef62ec3f1d316","target":"erdos:1063","trust":"signed"},{"evidence":"Materialized typed link between accepted findings.","inferred":true,"relation":"synthesized_from","source":"vf_dda44e804e8b97de","source_root":"sha256:540d4967071425f77c693e61f62053208b07d67667490dcb9eeef62ec3f1d316","target":"vf_e73b8515e9b26298","trust":"signed"},{"evidence":"Problem identity derived from the accepted finding's pinned source anchor.","inferre